Jan 6 2009 	Great property and location	Stayed this past weekend after New Year's for 2 nights. Got a great rate on a King Suite, which is a very nice room with separate seating area w/ sofa, nice large flat screen TV, great shower, nice bedding. Great modern decor, a little &quot;cold&quot; for my taste, but very nice. The thermostat in our room didn't seem to work, kept turning the heat down but temp stayed at 74 degrees and the heat wouldn't turn off so finally turned everything off and slept with the window cracked (it was 25 degrees at night). Early Sunday morning the fire alarm went off around 6:00am, but only lasted a few minutes. We figured it was a false alarm and didn't leave the room. No mention of it was ever made when we checked out the next day. I'm sure these are just minor glitches that are common in new hotels; was very pleased overall with the room, the hotel staff, the bar/lounge area, and the location which was great! Very close to Nolita, SoHo, Bowery, etc. with lots of cool little restaurants/shops/bars around to explore. The bar and restaurant had just opened a few weeks before I believe, and while there was no one in the bar area when we went for drinks both nights, the lounge/bar is beautiful and worth checking out. Not sure if it was quiet due to the wkend we went after the holidays or if it is so new no one knows about it yet, but I'm sure it will be the hotspot, especially in the summer when the outside bar opens. We've stayed at quite a few Thompson hotel properties, and have been always been pleased. I probably prefer 60 Thompson to this hotel, but would definately stay at the Thompson LES again.	
Jan 6 2009 	Modern boutique funky but missing something..	I have just returned from a 6 night stay at the Thompson LES over christmas. I echo the last poster and would agree this is a great hotel if you can get it for a reasonable price. We got a deal on Quickbook for $99 per night. For that price I could not fault it. The Hotel is brand new, and modern. They claim that the decor echoes the surrounding LES. That is obvious in its modern, urban, minimalist decor. There is a lot of concrete, monochrome, urban looking everything. The rooms are spacious enough by NY standards. I was lucky to get a 17th floor corner room with views of ESB, and Chrysler Building. The beds are very comfortable with good quality linens. The shower is huge, and has a rain shower head which is very powerful. There were some issues with the water whilst we were there. It was brown &amp; murky, and was turned off totally for 1 day. The toiletaries are Keihls. The safe/mini bar etc are what you would expect from a Hotel of this standard. There is a large LCD TV, but very poor choice of TV stations and no ECD to assist in finding anything. The new restaurant &amp; lounge are open, and the food is of a good standard. Overall the Hotel does what it says, but I feel is lacking something in terms of atmosphere or soul. The quality of the amenities I'm sure will be improved when all the facilities are finished. The urban vibe feels somewhat cold, as did the restaurant/lounge space. I think the Rivington captures this essence much better. If you can get the Hotel at a good rate, I would highly recomend it, bbut for the advertised rack rates, I think you could do a lot better.	
Dec 30 2008 	Worth it if you get a great price.	Stayed at the hotel for 3 days right after Christmas. We were able to get a fantastic rate of $129 per night for a King Suite, on Quikbook. At that price, this hotel is definitely a steal. If i had paid more than $250, i would have been disappointed with what they have to offer.The Rooms - the suites are really nice: great design, still spanking new, very large, fantastic hi def tv's and channels. Problem with sound from other rooms though. I could clearly hear when my neighbour talked slightly louder or had their tv on.The Service - the front desk, bellman are pleasant and obviously trying to be very serviceable. But they don't have a very good check-in system that they understand. Had the wrong rate listed on check in, then the wrong name after registering, and their equipment to scan id's didn't work.The Amenities - none to speak of really. it's just the rooms right now. If you want a lobby space to hang out in, or a great bar, or a place to grab something to eat...this is not the place. But Lower East Side has a ton of places just steps away, so this didn't matter to us.So overall, if you can get a great deal, go for it. Otherwise, if you're paying over $250, i'd say stay at the Rivington or another hotel that is fully set up.	
