Sep 5 2008 	Good potentatial when it is fully operational	Given previous reviews, I was somewhat anxious when checking in at the desk. First good surprise: I could get my room right away although it was only 1.30 PM. While I had booked a king studio (quite large and appointed with couches), I asked to move to another room, which turned out to be a queen, because of noisy neighbors (and also because the studio was rather dark).The two types of rooms offered the same modern, so-called industrial design; floor- to- ceiling windows, cement ceilings and and black wooden floor, shower with grey slates. Very Soho indeed and RIYL. The desk in the room was really narrow, but the bed was wide as was the flat TV screen.There are some interesting views from the rooms but it depends pretty much on which side and floor you are located. Some rooms, essentially those on Allen Street, are noisy. As other reviewers pointed out, there is virtually no service at the moment: no restaurant or bar, no spa or pool. In addition, most of the time, only one out of the three elevators was working. However, at the difference of a previous reviewer, I could get an internet connection (included in the rate).Also, a complementary, kind of basic breakfast was available in a small hospitality room on the 15th floor. This was not indicated when I booked my room and might be a sort of compensation for the .nuisance due to the ongoing construction within the hotel.Finally the front desk staff (with the men being especially elegant in trendy suits à la Paul Smith) was quite friendly, Most of them are young and some of them speak foreign language (notably Spanish). The bell guys were terrific and constantly servicing. I would not say the same of the concierge, who suggested restaurants by googling.The best part in this unfinished hotel is probably its neighborhood. Although increasingly invaded by tourists, the Lower east side is still a mixed and lively area of New York, with plenty of interesting shops, nice restaurants, charming streets and old fashioned buildings. An the Thompson LES is certainly a good base for exploring this part of the city.	
Sep 4 2008 	Nice hotel even if unfinished...	We just returned from a 2 day stay at the Thompson LES. We usually like to stay in Soho, but after getting an unbeatable rate on Quikbook for an average of $ 164.00 a day, we tried the LES this time. Actually this was our third stay at a Thompson Hotel in their opening phase. We had also stayed at their 6 Columbus and Gild Hall Hotel recently. The hotel is not finished yet, but we did not mind not having an in-house restaurant or pool. Check-in was OK, however there computer came up with a higher rate, but luckily I had a printout of my actual rate. I have been using Quikbook for many years and never had an issue before! We were told, that the room was not ready, but we could store our luggage and wait at their hospitality room on the 15th floor. Our question about an estimate when the room would be ready was never answered by the clerk, who seemed fairly unsure during the whole check-in process. We just thought, that we would stick around, if they thought it would be ready within the next 1/2 hour.We left the hotel and sure enough 15 min. later received a call, that the room was indeed ready. However we were already on the other side of town. When we returned later in the evening, we had to check-in all over again, since the previous clerk had not done it right, but the brazilian woman who helped us this time was very professional and also told us about the hotel and that a continental breakfast would be served in the hospitality room on the 15th floor. After check-in our stored luggage was nowhere to be found, however the previous bellboy had already brought it to our room during the day, which was nice - but lost in communication.Rooms were nice with hardwood floor, zebrawood furniture and all in all very modern sleek design. Loved the rain shower and the Kiehls amenities.Among all the 3 Thompson hotels, I personally thought the pastries served in the morning were much worse than at the 6 Columbus or the Gild Hall, but than it is hard to compete with the pastries from Bouley's bakery at the 6 Columbus. A plus was, that there was always plenty of complimentary Voss still water at the hospitality room! Another nice thing was, that when we called the hotel on our last evening, that we were on our way back from an early dinner and wanted to swing by the hotel with our cab to pick up the stored luggage, since we were running a little late to go the airport, the bellboy was already waiting with our bags in front of the hotel and we did not even had to stop to go in the hotel!All in all even with a few hickups, we had a nice stay, however having been at the Gild Hall as well as the 6 Columbus during their opening phase, I thought they were more professional than the LES.	
Sep 3 2008 	No Ready	We have a reservation to stay Sept 10th for 4 nights. I recently called the hotel to make sure everything would be up and running. They informed me the fitness centre, pool, restaurants and bars are NOT going to be ready until mid October. I will probably cancel and stay elsewhere. Rates are way too high for only receiving 50% of what is promised on the website!	
Sep 2 2008 	Great new hotel in SOHO	We stayed at the Thompson LES for the long weekend and had a great time. The hotel is new, so there were a few little issues that need to be sorted out, however we still loved the hotel.The service was excellent. All of the staff went above and beyond to ensure we had a nice stay. We had one issue with housekeeping. They did not make up our room on the second night. When we called down to tell them, they were ready to send someone up right away. Also, they provided turndown service the first night but not the second night- a little inconsistent, however not a big deal.The rooms are very nice. Sleek and modern. Spacious for NY standards. The pull out sofa is very uncomfortable though.The hospitality suite is a great place to relax. Nice terrace. Breakfast is served here. They provided fruits, coffee, water and pastries. Nice touch.The restaurant and pool are still not finished which explains the great price we got on the room.We would definitely stay here again and hope to go back when they are fully operating.	
Aug 31 2008 	Great hotel will be awesome when finished	We had an excellent stay at the LES, although it was not without a few hiccups. Beside the pool and bar not being finished many of the guest floors were not finished. Most of the time only one elevator was working at a time and briefly there were none. The staff was excellent. Every issue that we brought to their attention was dealt with promptly and efficiently. There were frequent apologies for the construction issues. Our room large by Manhattan standards and being on the 16th floor we had an awesome view. One story down was the hospitality suite where the continental breakfast was served. The patio here gave a sweeping view north, east and south of the building. The continental breakfast itself was decadent; cream puffs, chocolate croissants, and other sweet and savory pastries. There was also fruit and other standard breakfast fare.The decor at the Thompson LES is very sleek and modern and if that's not to your liking could be considered cold and unwelcoming. Some of the fixtures in the bathroom hav unfamiliar and sometimes baffling controls (there is a secret button on the shower control to allow the temperature to move higher that luke warm). The area is awesome with tons or restaurants and nightlife. There is a subway stop less than a block away.All in all a very nice stay. We'd like to go back once the pool is finished. I suspect the rates will go up once the hotel gets better known and works-out their remaining bugs. Hopefully we'll still be able to afford a stay there :)And don't forget to go around the corner onto Houston St. and hav lunch at Katz's Deli. Not just a landmark but amazingly good sandwichs.	
Aug 19 2008 	A Great Place to Stay	Stayed in August 2008What beautiful rooms! At night you can see the city lights. Floor to ceiling windows. A Great Location, close to many restaurants and shopping galore. Their restaurant and bar wasn't opened yet, but the front desk said they will open soon. Don't worry, plenty of food within walking distance. Staff at the hotel were plenty of help and very friendly. Not a bad price for NYC.I would definitely recommend this hotel to my friends.	
Aug 6 2008 	A Construction Zone I mean a Hotel	Having just returned from staying at the new Thompson Lower East Side, I was surprised and dismayed at what I found upon arrival. This hotel is NOT ready for business. Beside the fact that the hotel was very much still under construction (NO fitness center or pool as advertised on the Hotel website), there was NO wireless internet connection and the elevators were essentially either not working or barely working. When I voiced my exasperation upon check-in, the management was certainly apologetic, but wasn't able to do much to remedy the situation. The staff were young and enthusiastic but had their hands full running around trying to operate this unfinished project of a hotel. I would certainly wait a while before considering a return engagement.	
